1
00:00:00,335 --> 00:00:15,256
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:15,275 --> 00:00:27,132
Okay, so this moon, I've chosen these Atalokadama, these eight worldly conditions, concerns, wins, fortunes, vicissitudes.

3
00:00:27,152 --> 00:00:28,475
It's the ups and downs of life.

4
00:00:28,655 --> 00:00:30,257
I mean, that's basically what it is, yeah.

5
00:00:30,777 --> 00:00:33,238
I'll try and take these off, I think.

6
00:00:33,259 --> 00:00:35,661
So this is what the Buddha says.

7
00:00:36,502 --> 00:00:41,968
Gain obsesses the mind and loss obsesses the mind.

8
00:00:42,567 --> 00:00:47,792
Fame obsesses the mind and disrepute obsesses the mind.

9
00:00:48,673 --> 00:00:53,378
Blame obsesses the mind and praise obsesses the mind.

10
00:00:54,079 --> 00:00:59,164
Pleasure obsesses the mind and pain obsesses the mind.

11
00:01:00,258 --> 00:01:03,884
They are attracted to gain and repelled by loss.

12
00:01:04,564 --> 00:01:08,852
They are attracted to fame and repelled by disrepute.

13
00:01:09,733 --> 00:01:13,299
They are attracted to praise and repelled by blame.

14
00:01:14,501 --> 00:01:18,468
They are attracted to pleasure and repelled by pain.

15
00:01:19,174 --> 00:01:31,707
Thus involved with attraction and repulsion, they are not freed from birth, from old age and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection and anguish.

16
00:01:32,588 --> 00:01:34,790
They are not freed from suffering, I say.

17
00:01:36,313 --> 00:01:40,296
So that's the eight worldly conditions.

18
00:01:41,879 --> 00:01:46,683
Now, when we look at those conditions, you can see that they all arise out of a notion of a self.

19
00:01:47,525 --> 00:01:48,807
It's me that's blamed.

20
00:01:48,826 --> 00:01:50,870
It's me that's praised, etc., etc.

21
00:01:52,212 --> 00:01:57,081
And when we do that, of course, it just creates mental turbulence.

22
00:01:59,504 --> 00:02:05,534
When this happens at a societal level, then you can see communities being split, as we see these days.

23
00:02:05,614 --> 00:02:10,241
And of course, when it gets to an international level, well, there's always war going on.

24
00:02:12,094 --> 00:02:15,459
So what's it like to be freed of these worldly concerns?

25
00:02:15,739 --> 00:02:28,715
So in the discourse on the greatest blessings, the Buddha has stated how an awakened Arahant, how somebody who's fully liberated is unmoved by one of the eight worldly conditions.

26
00:02:29,695 --> 00:02:33,360
And he describes this as one of the great blessings.

27
00:02:33,862 --> 00:02:59,802
and it says that a mind unshaken by worldly vicissitudes sorrowless stainless and secure this is the greatest blessing and again we can extend that to families and countries and we might just get to a peaceful world so um what i've done is i've just made up questions around these eight

28
00:03:00,138 --> 00:03:11,670
factors just to give some idea of how we can use them just to reflect on the way we are with these fortunes and misfortunes.

29
00:03:12,793 --> 00:03:18,679
So if we take gain, for instance, you know, is to ask ourselves, what am I obsessing about?

30
00:03:18,979 --> 00:03:22,924
You know, what sort of an accumulation am I gathering?

31
00:03:22,984 --> 00:03:24,826
What collections do I have?

32
00:03:25,606 --> 00:03:26,989
You know, wealth, power,

33
00:03:27,997 --> 00:03:55,204
even though it's even though we might not have much wealth at all or indeed hardly any power the point is this this obsession about it control how much energy do we give to it you see um and how much time do we waste brooding and planning over these sorts of things

34
00:03:55,572 --> 00:04:07,473
And then once we can bring a past event to mind as a practice, we can get in touch with that feeling, that craving, that holding on, you know, the cramped grip.

35
00:04:08,736 --> 00:04:09,919
What does that feel like?

36
00:04:13,104 --> 00:04:18,732
And to try and separate that from what you might call just an ordinary wholesome desire.

37
00:04:18,771 --> 00:04:21,877
I mean, we need money, we need friends, et cetera, et cetera.

38
00:04:22,297 --> 00:04:26,062
But there's a way of having that without that obsessiveness.

39
00:04:28,464 --> 00:04:29,687
And then, of course, there's loss.

40
00:04:29,987 --> 00:04:31,389
And everybody feels that.

41
00:04:32,209 --> 00:04:33,211
You might lose your job.

42
00:04:33,271 --> 00:04:34,252
What does that feel like?

43
00:04:34,333 --> 00:04:37,276
If you have lost your job in the past, how did that feel?

44
00:04:37,737 --> 00:04:41,221
The despair, the confusion, the anxiety, panic?

45
00:04:41,944 --> 00:04:46,591
So much depends upon our work, you know, and the wage that we have.

46
00:04:48,194 --> 00:04:53,262
And then there's the self-worth that we have from our work, you know, the sense of status.

47
00:04:53,322 --> 00:04:54,925
But we'll come to that a bit later.

48
00:04:56,367 --> 00:04:59,732
So we have to just ask ourselves, what if I let go of that?

49
00:04:59,872 --> 00:05:04,779
What if I just let go of the obsessiveness and just be more content with what I have?

50
00:05:08,437 --> 00:05:21,752
And by going to a past occasion and investigating it and reflecting on it, it just helps us to be prepared for the next time.

51
00:05:23,675 --> 00:05:33,687
So we're not so shocked when we lose things, lose our work, lose money on the horses and stuff like that.

52
00:05:35,370 --> 00:05:36,833
So the next one is praise.

53
00:05:36,973 --> 00:05:51,574
So again, we look back and we think, well, what have I done or said or I am doing or saying which has an underlying demand for praise, for admiration, for compliments, for appreciation?

54
00:05:51,595 --> 00:05:53,557
I mean, how does that feel?

55
00:05:53,798 --> 00:05:54,759
Is it necessary?

56
00:05:55,581 --> 00:06:00,567
And how does that reflect on ourselves and how we're judging ourselves?

57
00:06:01,206 --> 00:06:10,059
And how we feel embarrassed when we suddenly realise that we've said something or done something just to be praised, just to be admired.

58
00:06:12,642 --> 00:06:16,649
And what would have happened if you hadn't had that intention in that particular case?

59
00:06:17,810 --> 00:06:20,553
And what should the attitude have been?

60
00:06:24,720 --> 00:06:26,903
When it comes to blame, well, nobody likes that.

61
00:06:27,002 --> 00:06:30,487
Nobody likes to be blamed for anything, you know.

62
00:06:30,704 --> 00:06:43,204
And again, to bring up an occasion in the past where we've been blamed and we've been judged and we've been criticized, you know, and just to get to the hurt of that and how we reacted.

63
00:06:43,245 --> 00:06:47,651
And sometimes, of course, we react silently within ourselves.

64
00:06:47,692 --> 00:06:56,846
We spend hours getting our own back in these fantasies, throwing people on fires and chucking them off bridges and things like that.

65
00:06:58,007 --> 00:07:02,540
So it's getting in touch with those feelings and naming them for what they are, you see.

66
00:07:03,201 --> 00:07:05,086
So what is it like to be humiliated?

67
00:07:06,331 --> 00:07:10,482
Instead of hiding that from ourselves, suppressing it because of our pride,

68
00:07:10,747 --> 00:07:19,939
It's to let it up, you see, to let up and just feel it and to know that if I can just allow these things to manifest, they're actually dying out.

69
00:07:19,999 --> 00:07:21,480
They're actually curing.

70
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:22,041
Right.

71
00:07:22,581 --> 00:07:24,264
And some of these things are very difficult.

72
00:07:24,545 --> 00:07:29,250
You know, the hurt, the humiliation is it really hurts the ego.

73
00:07:29,310 --> 00:07:31,473
I mean, it really punches the self.

74
00:07:33,415 --> 00:07:37,100
And if we're afraid of criticism, does that make us timid?

75
00:07:37,519 --> 00:07:37,740
Yeah.

76
00:07:37,940 --> 00:07:39,101
Does that make us timid?

77
00:07:41,764 --> 00:07:55,944
And then when we have been blamed and it has been our fault, have we been humble enough to accept that, you know, and try and do something about it and not let that rumble on afterwards about self-criticism?

78
00:07:55,983 --> 00:07:56,944
You know, I'm such a fool.

79
00:07:56,966 --> 00:07:57,685
I'm an idiot.

80
00:07:57,887 --> 00:07:58,807
How could I have done that?

81
00:07:59,028 --> 00:08:06,978
See, it's just it's just being able to let go, to let go of something, you know.

82
00:08:10,115 --> 00:08:13,278
And then we have the area of success and failure.

83
00:08:14,238 --> 00:08:15,680
So again, it's much the same thing.

84
00:08:15,740 --> 00:08:21,367
You bring to mind a past occasion when you feel you've been successful, a job well done.

85
00:08:21,968 --> 00:08:26,172
And there's nothing wrong with appropriate congratulations, you know.

86
00:08:27,533 --> 00:08:30,497
But again, it's this business of hanging on to that success.

87
00:08:32,860 --> 00:08:38,586
I've got here just what the Buddha says about somebody who becomes an Arahant.

88
00:08:39,730 --> 00:08:57,509
He says that someone who's an Arahant with their taints, taints are the roots of all our defilements, a craving for pleasure, craving to become, and ignorance, the basic ignorance of self.

89
00:08:58,931 --> 00:09:03,436
And these are the roots from which all these defilements arise.

90
00:09:04,517 --> 00:09:06,379
So he says when those are destroyed,

91
00:09:06,966 --> 00:09:23,432
and has lived the holy life, done what has to be done or had to be done, laid down the burden, reached the goal, destroyed the fetters of becoming, and is completely liberated through final desire.

92
00:09:23,994 --> 00:09:28,461
So you can see, I mean, you know, it's that sense of completion.

93
00:09:28,562 --> 00:09:30,644
What had to be done has been done.

94
00:09:31,097 --> 00:09:37,384
And if you look at your life where you've really sort of completed something, it's done, it's finished, it's gone.

95
00:09:37,965 --> 00:09:39,546
There's a sense of joy about that.

96
00:09:39,765 --> 00:09:40,025
Yeah.

97
00:09:40,486 --> 00:09:52,879
And lay down the burden, you know, the sense of relief of laying down the burden, laying down the burden of being a human being, basically.

98
00:09:52,899 --> 00:09:55,821
And of course, the taste of Nibbana is the joy of freedom.

99
00:09:56,282 --> 00:09:56,402
Right.

100
00:09:56,422 --> 00:09:58,563
So that's that's where we're heading.

101
00:09:58,583 --> 00:10:00,666
It's good to remind ourselves about that.

102
00:10:03,397 --> 00:10:08,652
And then, of course, when when we are praised, we tend to personalize things.

103
00:10:09,092 --> 00:10:12,282
So immediately it's not it's not the job that's being praised.

104
00:10:12,341 --> 00:10:12,923
It's me.

105
00:10:13,504 --> 00:10:13,865
Right.

106
00:10:13,885 --> 00:10:14,908
I'm amazing.

107
00:10:15,451 --> 00:10:17,777
I get very big headed.

108
00:10:23,629 --> 00:10:41,890
And sometimes, you know, if you catch yourself like that, if you catch yourself being big headed, you know, and full of self praise and all that, then again becomes a sort of and you sort of notice that other people are seeing it as big headedness.

109
00:10:42,371 --> 00:10:45,434
And of course, that again produces a sense of shame within us.

110
00:10:49,110 --> 00:10:56,326
So all these things, you see, just recognize all the ego stuff as unnecessary evaluation tags.

111
00:10:56,807 --> 00:10:57,869
Just let them fade away.

112
00:10:57,928 --> 00:11:02,479
And eventually, as the Buddha said, they just fall off.

113
00:11:04,230 --> 00:11:29,596
uh failure oh that's the next one failure so a job didn't turn out well a relationship sadly ended how's it feel you know not to achieve something uh even if you've put a lot of work into it and it just hasn't happened you know so again you get this personalization the job failed therefore i'm a failure yeah the relationship failed so i'm i'm unlovable right

114
00:11:30,336 --> 00:11:36,346
And it's sort of reflecting on that and recognizing that those personalization of things are just not necessary.

115
00:11:36,426 --> 00:11:37,928
They just add suffering to it.

116
00:11:43,557 --> 00:11:53,052
And if it was a genuine mistake or whatever, we can be realistic about it and to make sure that we don't repeat that same mistake.

117
00:11:53,533 --> 00:11:55,836
But then again, of course, circumstances change.

118
00:11:55,895 --> 00:11:59,061
We don't have that total control anymore.

119
00:12:04,373 --> 00:12:06,434
And finally, there's pleasure and pain.

120
00:12:06,534 --> 00:12:09,937
So pleasure, of course, both mental and physical pleasure.

121
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:13,621
We're always seeking that.

122
00:12:13,662 --> 00:12:17,024
We're always trying to be in that sort of pleasurable state.

123
00:12:18,066 --> 00:12:26,114
But it's a case of, again, not attaching to it, not making it something that is repeatable.

124
00:12:26,475 --> 00:12:33,081
So when we have something joyful, something pleasant, to accept that it's come to an end and there's no need to go any further with it.

125
00:12:33,735 --> 00:12:39,043
and to find out how we experience desire.

126
00:12:39,063 --> 00:12:46,937
So sometimes, for instance, when it comes to food, you don't feel hungry, so you're not attracted so much to the cake.

127
00:12:48,379 --> 00:12:52,404
But sometimes when you are hungry, you can't stop yourself from eating the whole cake.

128
00:12:52,885 --> 00:12:58,815
So there's something about desire which is separate from seeing something that is pleasant.

129
00:12:59,268 --> 00:12:59,587
Right.

130
00:13:00,089 --> 00:13:03,413
There's that movement towards it of wanting, wanting, wanting.

131
00:13:03,833 --> 00:13:08,821
And then to make that distinction between the desire and the action.

132
00:13:09,081 --> 00:13:16,311
So remember, in Buddhist psychology, this is really crucial because when something is a desire, nothing's actually happened.

133
00:13:16,571 --> 00:13:17,511
It's just potential.

134
00:13:18,052 --> 00:13:23,200
But as soon as you decide to let that energy go and produce something, a thought or

135
00:13:23,179 --> 00:13:47,500
speech something that you do there becomes an action and that action goes out into a matrix of relationships on the outside but it's also moves into the inner matrix of our psyche yeah and that's that's what we've been by karma action and so we're trying to make a distinction here between indulgence and enjoyment

136
00:13:47,884 --> 00:13:54,134
And we do that, and the Buddha's always on about this, by restraining ourselves, right?

137
00:13:54,153 --> 00:13:55,936
That's very difficult in our society.

138
00:13:56,116 --> 00:13:57,999
We're not expected to restrain.

139
00:13:58,058 --> 00:14:00,363
In fact, everybody wants us to indulge.

140
00:14:01,003 --> 00:14:12,740
But the act of restraint gets us in touch with the unacceptable level, you might say, from a Dharma point of view of desire, right?

141
00:14:12,759 --> 00:14:14,623
So in other words, nothing's wrong with appetite.

142
00:14:15,102 --> 00:14:16,304
Everything's wrong with greed.

143
00:14:18,783 --> 00:14:19,904
And then finally pain.

144
00:14:19,965 --> 00:14:22,008
So pain can be very difficult, you know.

145
00:14:23,249 --> 00:14:34,004
And I think one of the things we have to be careful of here is that we don't take what pain comes to us as some sort of karmic resolve.

146
00:14:34,125 --> 00:14:35,606
You know, I deserve the pain.

147
00:14:37,649 --> 00:14:42,758
We're not in charge of the body and the body has its own weaknesses.

148
00:14:43,298 --> 00:14:46,001
And sometimes when the pain comes, it's to do with genetics.

149
00:14:46,022 --> 00:14:48,485
It's not to do with the person themselves.

150
00:14:49,140 --> 00:14:55,041
So it's up to us to decide whether this pain is something that I want to work with.

151
00:14:55,764 --> 00:15:01,142
So you're working with it in terms of getting that right relationship with pain of patience.

152
00:15:01,442 --> 00:15:04,687
understanding what pain is at different levels.

153
00:15:04,888 --> 00:15:11,116
You know, at one level, at the basic level of contact, pain is just sensation, right?

154
00:15:11,136 --> 00:15:19,107
It's when it becomes a feeling, when it's acknowledged as a feeling that you get the sense of pain and then you get that reaction of not wanting it.

155
00:15:20,811 --> 00:15:30,183
But if you can't do that sort of investigation and you haven't got the patience for it, then, you know, take an aspirin, do something.

156
00:15:31,918 --> 00:15:44,643
I was just thinking then of the Act of Parliament that we've had, well, it's not completely passed, about assisted dying, you see.

157
00:15:45,764 --> 00:15:52,677
And it's an area which Buddhists have to really think about and where they are personally with that.

158
00:15:53,332 --> 00:16:10,629
And when pain gets to a point which is cannot be assuaged by any of the morphines and all that sort of stuff, then one has to decide for oneself whether, you know, it's a time to put an end to one's life and whatnot.

159
00:16:11,230 --> 00:16:15,354
And there are various degrees of understanding as to what is right and what is wrong.

160
00:16:15,374 --> 00:16:18,057
But ultimately, it's the individual.

161
00:16:18,317 --> 00:16:20,379
It's for them to feel OK with it.

162
00:16:21,139 --> 00:16:21,399
Yeah.

163
00:16:22,256 --> 00:16:23,899
So that's a big topic, that.

164
00:16:30,126 --> 00:16:38,096
So again, going back to the Buddha and just giving him a bit of time to quote there.

165
00:16:38,155 --> 00:16:45,445
Here we go.

166
00:16:45,465 --> 00:16:50,390
So when gain arises for an uninstructed, run-of-the-mill person,

167
00:16:51,467 --> 00:16:52,649
They do not reflect.

168
00:16:53,190 --> 00:16:54,611
Gain has arisen for me.

169
00:16:54,631 --> 00:16:59,038
It is inconstant, stressful and subject to change.

170
00:16:59,860 --> 00:17:02,503
They do not discern it as it has come to be.

171
00:17:03,163 --> 00:17:04,365
So that's what's missing.

172
00:17:04,665 --> 00:17:10,013
We presume that once I've got something, it's just going to grow, that it's not going to leave me.

173
00:17:10,473 --> 00:17:19,787
But it's a good thing to be able to remind oneself that whatever I have received, which is bringing me joy, pleasure, etc.,

174
00:17:20,189 --> 00:17:22,573
This too will pass, you know.

175
00:17:23,233 --> 00:17:33,230
So one of the things I one of the things I try to remind people to do is that after lunch, you know, to say to yourself, well, this is one less lunch in this lifetime.

176
00:17:35,354 --> 00:17:39,800
We can we can measure our lives by how many lunches we have, how many breakfasts we have.

177
00:17:43,627 --> 00:17:55,625
And then those people who are not instructed, you see, they welcome, they sort of grab hold of an arisen gain and rebel against an arisen loss.

178
00:17:56,227 --> 00:18:02,396
And so it's the same with status and disgrace, with praise and blame and with pleasure and pain.

179
00:18:03,458 --> 00:18:07,964
As they are thus engaged in welcoming and rebelling,

180
00:18:08,636 --> 00:18:16,244
They are not released from birth, aging and death, from sorrows, lamentations, pain, distresses and despairs.

181
00:18:16,325 --> 00:18:21,430
They are not released, I tell you, from suffering and unhappiness.

182
00:18:24,573 --> 00:18:34,363
And of course, those who are awakened, those who have developed to some degree, then, of course, they don't welcome it in that sense of wanting to indulge it.

183
00:18:34,403 --> 00:18:37,445
They just receive it.

184
00:18:38,589 --> 00:18:41,095
And this is the difference, he says, the distinction.

185
00:18:41,154 --> 00:18:50,553
This is the distinguishing factor between a well-instructed disciple of the noble ones and an uninstructed, run-of-the-mill person.

186
00:18:51,134 --> 00:18:56,083
So what's this underlying attitude that we're trying to develop to all these worldly conditions?

187
00:18:56,684 --> 00:18:57,465
It's equanimity.

188
00:18:57,807 --> 00:18:58,768
Yeah, it's equanimity.

189
00:18:59,288 --> 00:19:00,632
And this comes about

190
00:19:00,915 --> 00:19:07,383
more and more as identity becomes about a self becomes less and less.

191
00:19:07,903 --> 00:19:14,671
The less we personalize things, the more we find ourselves at ease with the way things are.

192
00:19:15,872 --> 00:19:22,420
And it's this sense of self which is producing all the problems.

193
00:19:22,720 --> 00:19:29,067
And we undermine that by reminding ourselves what the correct or should we say,

194
00:19:29,434 --> 00:19:32,637
the more wholesome, skillful attitude ought to be.

195
00:19:33,618 --> 00:19:36,362
And it's, what do they say?

196
00:19:36,382 --> 00:19:37,583
It's a working process.

197
00:19:39,224 --> 00:19:41,446
I wouldn't talk about progress.

198
00:19:41,907 --> 00:19:43,730
See, don't get involved with progress.

199
00:19:43,789 --> 00:19:45,411
Just get involved with process.

200
00:19:45,912 --> 00:19:55,141
How do I, you know, get rid of these wrong attitudes that I have to these eight worldly winds, which are going to happen anyway in my life?

201
00:19:55,442 --> 00:19:56,843
You know, we're not going to stop it.

202
00:19:58,949 --> 00:20:13,424
So it's one of the attractions of the Buddha's teachings that he really is also, you know, buried his teachings as well into daily life.

203
00:20:15,166 --> 00:20:20,452
So it's not just meditation and beautiful mental states and developing metta from the heart.

204
00:20:20,953 --> 00:20:28,602
It's actually driving us into right action, right eightfold path, right speech, right action and right livelihood.

205
00:20:29,289 --> 00:20:35,296
And one of the things we have to do is just be able to handle these eight worldly winds.

206
00:20:36,738 --> 00:20:37,278
Very good.

207
00:20:37,739 --> 00:20:40,300
I hope that these words have been of some assistance.

208
00:20:40,421 --> 00:20:42,743
They have not caused confusion.

209
00:20:43,243 --> 00:20:54,055
And that by your careful investigation of these eight worldly winds, you will soon be liberated from all suffering.

